{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-04-04T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before sunrise, the moorland clock punches in—and the dance floor opens. Male black grouse don't send invites; they boom them. Welcome to lekking season, where romance is competitive, noisy and strictly outdoors.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.GrouseGuff_ROW0536575976_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.GrouseGuff_ROW0536575976_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Black grouse males facing off on a lekking site, Estonia","Copyright":"© Sven Zacek/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260404_GrouseGuff\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Black+grouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260404_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260404_GrouseGuff"},"Ssd":"20260404","Name":"GrouseGuff","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0536575976","FullDateString":"4 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Some bridges in Amsterdam just get you across a canal. The Armbrug does more—it seems to wave hello as you pass. Nestled over the Oudezijds Voorburgwal canal, its name, meaning 'arm bridge,' refers to the nearby Oudezijds Armsteeg (Old Side Arm Alley), not a literal limb, but it's easy to imagine it greeting cyclists and pedestrians along the way.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ArmbrugBridge_ROW0384861076_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ArmbrugBridge_ROW0384861076_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Armbrug bridge, Amsterdam, Netherlands","Copyright":"© Alexander Spatari/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260403_ArmbrugBridge\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Armbrug+bridge+Amsterdam&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260403_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260403_ArmbrugBridge"},"Ssd":"20260403","Name":"ArmbrugBridge","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0384861076","FullDateString":"3 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring announces itself across California's Central Valley with the first bursts of wildflowers following the winter rains. Stretching about 720 kilometres from north to south and covering approximately 51,800 square kilometres, the valley is one of the world's most productive agricultural regions. In early spring, however, an older identity briefly resurfaces. From March through April, native annuals such as goldfields, tidy tips and owl's clover quickly germinate once temperature and soil moisture are optimal. They race to complete their life cycles before the long dry season begins.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WildflowerValley_ROW2763453477_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WildflowerValley_ROW2763453477_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Wildflower bloom, Central Valley, California, United States","Copyright":"© Jeff Lewis/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260402_WildflowerValley\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Central+Valley+California&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260402_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260402_WildflowerValley"},"Ssd":"20260402","Name":"WildflowerValley","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2763453477","FullDateString":"2 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today, let's hop into the world of one of nature's smallest yet most hardworking ambassadors. Frogs may not wear crowns—unless you believe in Frog Kings—but they do rule quietly behind the scenes. By keeping insect populations in check, they help ecosystems stay balanced. Even more impressive? Their sensitive skin also means they react quickly to changes in their surroundings, which is why scientists often look at frogs to understand the health of wetlands and forests. Talk about living barometers.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_ROW2089186925_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_ROW2089186925_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Japanese tree frog in a pink morning glory","Copyright":"© Tetsuya Tanooka/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Japanese+tree+frog&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260401_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog"},"Ssd":"20260401","Name":"JapaneseTreeFrog","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2089186925","FullDateString":"1 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Paradise Cave makes a powerful first impression the moment visitors step inside. This vast limestone cavern lies deep within Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park in central Vietnam, a region marked by rugged mountains and countless hidden caves. Stretching 31 kilometres, Paradise Cave is one of Asia's longest dry caves, and its scale is immediately apparent. High ceilings rise above the walkways and layered patterns formed by mineral-rich water over millions of years line the walls.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_ROW1547496612_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_ROW1547496612_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Paradise Cave, Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park, Vietnam","Copyright":"© Pakawat Thongcharoen/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Paradise+Cave+Vietnam&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260331_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave"},"Ssd":"20260331","Name":"ParadiseCave","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1547496612","FullDateString":"31 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The demoiselle crane is a small yet striking migratory bird found across Central Asia, from its breeding grounds in the steppes of Kazakhstan, Mongolia and northern China, to its wintering grounds in India, Nepal and parts of Africa. With its elegant appearance—slender neck, long legs and beautiful plumage—it is often considered one of the most graceful crane species. They are known for their intricate courtship dances, during which pairs engage in synchronised movements and calls, creating a beautiful spectacle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_ROW7826149929_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_ROW7826149929_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Demoiselle cranes, India","Copyright":"© Axel Gomille/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Demoiselle+cranes&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260330_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes"},"Ssd":"20260330","Name":"IndiaCranes","Market":"ROW","Hash":"7826149929","FullDateString":"30 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Peggy's Cove is a small yet captivating village on the rugged coast of Nova Scotia that offers a glimpse of life by the sea. The village's most famous landmark is Peggy's Point Lighthouse—also known as Peggy's Cove Lighthouse—first established in 1868 and replaced by the current structure in 1915. For over a century, it has guided ships through the ever-changing Atlantic waters, serving as a timeless symbol of coastal life. The surrounding landscape, with its windswept beauty and crashing waves, feels almost untouched by time.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_ROW0925207018_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_ROW0925207018_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Peggy's Point Lighthouse, Atlantic Coast, Nova Scotia, Canada","Copyright":"© Prashanth Bala/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Peggys+Point+Lighthouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260329_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse"},"Ssd":"20260329","Name":"PeggysLighthouse","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0925207018","FullDateString":"29 Mar 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A beach born from fire rarely does so subtly, yet Papagayo Beach manages exactly that. The shoreline we see today rests on the southern edge of Lanzarote, one of Spain's Canary Islands. Tropical fantasy? More like volcanic precision. Millions of years ago, this land rose in successive layers of basalt and ash thrust upward by submarine eruptions.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PlayaPapagayo_ROW1699824695_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PlayaPapagayo_ROW1699824695_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Papagayo Beach, Lanzarote, Canary Islands, Spain","Copyright":"© Gavin Hellier/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260411_PlayaPapagayo\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lanzarote+Canary+Islands+Spain&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260411_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260411_PlayaPapagayo"},"Ssd":"20260411","Name":"PlayaPapagayo","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1699824695","FullDateString":"11 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ever caught siblings plotting? In Karula National Park, Estonia, it looks as though these two red fox kits froze mid-conspiracy, their expressions mirrored in curiosity and caution. They're not just springtime fluff; they're apprentices in survival. Born in litters averaging four to six kits, foxes grow quickly, their underground den becoming a wrestling ring, classroom and testing ground. Older kits often help feed, guard and teach the younger ones, turning play into practice and mischief into muscle memory.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FoxSiblings_ROW1554598734_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FoxSiblings_ROW1554598734_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Two young red foxes at Karula National Park, Estonia","Copyright":"© Sven Zacek/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260410_FoxSiblings\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Karula+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260410_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260410_FoxSiblings"},"Ssd":"20260410","Name":"FoxSiblings","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1554598734","FullDateString":"10 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Water spills in clean lines at Sgwd yr Eira, one of South Wales' most distinctive waterfalls. Its Welsh name means 'Waterfall of Snow,' referring to the pale curtain of water sliding over the rock face. What sets this waterfall apart is access. A narrow path leads visitors behind the falling water, immersing them in sound, light and movement at close range. Sgwd yr Eira lies within Bannau Brycheiniog National Park, often called 'Waterfall Country' for its network of rivers and falls carved into wooded gorges. Well-marked trails connect this waterfall to others along the River Hepste, making it a popular stop on longer hikes. Above the valleys, the landscape opens into rolling moorland and long ridgelines where upland paths are shaped by wind and changing weather. These contrasts define the Bannau Brycheiniog, where open, exposed uplands give way to sheltered water, tying the landscape together.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WalesWaterfall_ROW4607856907_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WalesWaterfall_ROW4607856907_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Sgwd yr Eira waterfall, Bannau Brycheiniog National Park, Wales","Copyright":"© Guy Edwardes/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260409_WalesWaterfall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bannau+Brycheiniog+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260409_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260409_WalesWaterfall"},"Ssd":"20260409","Name":"WalesWaterfall","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4607856907","FullDateString":"9 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Seattle's waterfront seems suspended between sea and sky as soft light settles on the horizon. The city is named after Chief Si'ahl, a leader of the Duwamish and Suquamish peoples, whose legacy remains important to the region's identity. Steep streets lead down to piers that sweep across Elliott Bay. Rising above the shoreline, the Space Needle stands out as the city's most recognisable landmark. Pike Place Market, founded in 1907, overlooks the waterfront and continues to anchor daily life and long-held traditions.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_ROW1229095485_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_ROW1229095485_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Seattle, Washington, United States","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Seattle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260408_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise"},"Ssd":"20260408","Name":"SeattleSunrise","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1229095485","FullDateString":"8 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The beaver—buck-toothed, paddle-tailed and famously industrious—has been reshaping freshwater landscapes for millions of years. With their iron-reinforced orange incisors, these skilled rodents cut down trees and build dams that slow the flow of water, improve its quality and create wetlands that support a remarkable diversity of life. Their sturdy lodges, made of branches and mud, have underwater entrances that protect them from predators and keep their families safe.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_ROW1082400008_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_ROW1082400008_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Beaver, Germany","Copyright":"© Andyworks/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Beaver+rodent&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260407_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait"},"Ssd":"20260407","Name":"BeaverPortrait","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1082400008","FullDateString":"7 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Picture northern Japan in the early 1600s. Castles stood at the crossroads of politics, trade and governance. Across generations, they came to reflect not only moments of tension but also endurance, adaptation and everyday life. Today's image features Hirosaki Castle, completed in 1611 under the Tsugaru clan, an influential Japanese samurai family. It was also known as Takaoka Castle. Fires, lightning strikes and strategic rebuilding reshaped parts of the complex, yet the castle continued to anchor local administration and culture throughout the Edo period. After the feudal system collapsed in the nineteenth century, its moats, gates and watchtowers survived as the grounds gradually became a public park famed for its thousands of cherry trees planted in the early twentieth century. Today the site remains a cultural landmark and one of Japan's most celebrated cherry‑blossom destinations.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_ROW0945099429_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_ROW0945099429_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Hirosaki Castle with cherry blossoms, Hirosaki, Japan","Copyright":"© Glenn Waters/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hirosaki+Castle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260406_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms"},"Ssd":"20260406","Name":"CastleBlossoms","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0945099429","FullDateString":"6 Apr 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ever wondered what a high-mountain lake looks like before the hikers arrive? At over 1,940 metres above sea level, Lake Gentau sits quietly in the Pyrenees of south-west France, its cold waters reflecting granite slopes and shifting clouds. Reached on foot from the Ossau Valley, the lake has long been a pause point for shepherds and walkers crossing these summer pastures. Look up and you will spot the dark volcanic shape of Pic du Midi d'Ossau nearby. Why does that peak matter? For centuries it served as a natural landmark guiding travellers through the mountain passes between France and Spain. Today it sits near the western boundary of the Pyrenees National Park. On calm days the surface turns mirror-still, reflecting sky, rock and the sharp outline of the Ossau peak. Not a bad reward for a mountain walk.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LacGentau_ROW3338740451_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LacGentau_ROW3338740451_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lake Gentau in the French Pyrenees, Pyrénées-Atlantiques, France","Copyright":"© MICHAUX Stéphane/Hemis.fr/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260405_LacGentau\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lake+Gentau+French+Pyrenees&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260405_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260405_LacGentau"},"Ssd":"20260405","Name":"LacGentau","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3338740451","FullDateString":"5 Apr 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Imej hari ini","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"Ketahui selanjutnya","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"Derma sekarang","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"Fakta ringkas:"